# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: infrastructure-drift
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:infrastructure-drift/change-management-engineering] The **change request management** process in systems engineering is the process of requesting, determining attainability, planning, implementing, and evaluating of changes to a system.
[src:infrastructure-drift/change-management-engineering] Its main goals are to support the processing and traceability of changes to an interconnected set of factors.
[src:infrastructure-drift/change-management-engineering] There is considerable overlap and confusion between change request management, change control and configuration management.
[src:infrastructure-drift/change-management-engineering] The definition below does not yet integrate these areas.
[src:infrastructure-drift/change-management-engineering] Change request management has been embraced for its ability to deliver benefits by improving the affected system and thereby satisfying "customer needs," but has also been criticized for its potential to confuse and needlessly complicate change administration.
[src:infrastructure-drift/change-management-engineering] In some cases, notably in the Information Technology domain, more funds and work are put into system maintenance (and change request management) than into the initial creation of a system.
[src:infrastructure-drift/change-management-engineering] Typical investment by organizations during initial implementation of large ERP systems is 15 to 20 percent of overall budget.
[src:infrastructure-drift/change-management-engineering] Change request management is also of great importance in the field of manufacturing, which is confronted with many changes due to increasing and worldwide competition, technological advances and demanding customers.
[src:infrastructure-drift/change-management-engineering] Because many systems tend to change and evolve as they are used, the problems of these industries are experienced to some degree in many others.
[src:infrastructure-drift/change-management-engineering] Notes: In the process below, it is arguable that the change committee should be responsible not only for accept/reject decisions, but also prioritization, which influences how change requests are batched for processing.
[src:infrastructure-drift/change-management-engineering] For the description of the change request management process, the meta-modeling technique is used.
[src:infrastructure-drift/change-management-engineering] Figure 1 depicts the process-data diagram, which is explained in this section.
[src:infrastructure-drift/change-management-engineering] There are six main activities, which jointly form the change request management process.
[src:infrastructure-drift/change-management-engineering] They are: Identify potential change, Analyze change request, Evaluate change, Plan change, Implement change and Review and close change.
[src:infrastructure-drift/change-management-engineering] These activities are executed by four different roles, which are discussed in Table 1.
[src:infrastructure-drift/change-management-engineering] The activities (or their sub-activities, if applicable) themselves are described in Table 2.
[src:infrastructure-drift/change-management-engineering] Besides activities, the process-data diagram (Figure 1) also shows the deliverables of each activity, i.e. the data.
[src:infrastructure-drift/change-management-engineering] These deliverables or concepts are described in Table 3; in this context, the most important concepts are: CHANGE REQUEST and CHANGE LOG ENTRY.
[src:infrastructure-drift/change-management-engineering] A few concepts are defined by the author (i.e. lack a reference), because either no (good) definitions could be found, or they are the obvious result of an activity.
[src:infrastructure-drift/change-management-engineering] These concepts are marked with an asterisk (‘*’).
[src:infrastructure-drift/change-management-engineering] Properties of concepts have been left out of the model, because most of them are trivial and the diagram could otherwise quickly become too complex.
[src:infrastructure-drift/change-management-engineering] CHANGE REQUEST, SYSTEM RELEASE) lend themselves for the versioning approach as proposed by Weerd, but this has also been left out due to diagram complexity constraints.
[src:infrastructure-drift/change-management-engineering] Besides just ‘changes’, one can also distinguish deviations and waivers.
[src:infrastructure-drift/change-management-engineering] A deviation is an authorization (or a request for it) to depart from a requirement of an item, prior to the creation of it.
[src:infrastructure-drift/change-management-engineering] A waiver is essentially the same, but than during or after creation of the item.
[src:infrastructure-drift/change-management-engineering] These two approaches can be viewed as minimalistic change request management (i.e. no real solution to the problem at hand).
[src:infrastructure-drift/change-management-engineering] A good example of the change request management process in action can be found in software development.
[src:infrastructure-drift/change-management-engineering] Often users report bugs or desire new functionality from their software programs, which leads to a change request.
[src:infrastructure-drift/change-management-engineering] The product software company then looks into the technical and economical feasibility of implementing this change and consequently it decides whether the change will actually be realized.
[src:infrastructure-drift/change-management-engineering] If that indeed is the case, the change has to be planned, for example through the usage of function points.
[src:infrastructure-drift/change-management-engineering] The actual execution of the change leads to the creation and/or alteration of software code and when this change is propagated it probably causes other code fragments to change as well.
[src:infrastructure-drift/change-management-engineering] After the initial test results seem satisfactory, the documentation can be brought up to date and be released, together with the software.
[src:infrastructure-drift/change-management-engineering] Finally, the project manager verifies the change and closes this entry in the change log.
[src:infrastructure-drift/change-management-engineering] Another typical area for change request management in the way it is treated here, is the manufacturing domain.
[src:infrastructure-drift/change-management-engineering] Take for instance the design and production of a car.
[src:infrastructure-drift/change-management-engineering] If for example the vehicle's air bags are found to automatically fill with air after driving long distances, this will without a doubt lead to customer complaints (or hopefully problem reports during the testing phase).
[src:infrastructure-drift/change-management-engineering] In turn, these produce a change request (see Figure 2 on the right), which will probably justify a change.
[src:infrastructure-drift/change-management-engineering] Nevertheless, a – most likely simplistic – cost and benefit analysis has to be done, after which the change request can be approved.
[src:infrastructure-drift/change-management-engineering] Following an analysis of the impact on the car design and production schedules, the planning for the implementation of the change can be created.
[src:infrastructure-drift/change-management-engineering] According to this planning, the change can actually be realized, after which the new version of the car is hopefully thoroughly tested before it is released to the public.
[src:infrastructure-drift/change-management-engineering] Since complex processes can be very sensitive to even small changes, proper management of change to industrial process plants is recognized as critical to safety.
[src:infrastructure-drift/change-management-engineering] Undocumented, not properly risk assessed changes are a recipe for disaster.
[src:infrastructure-drift/change-management-engineering] An eminent example of this is the Flixborough explosion, where improvised changes involving the bypassing of a stage in a reactor train was at the origin of the accident.
[src:infrastructure-drift/change-management-engineering] The change had not been properly thought out, documented and risk-assessed, so that the event of breach of containment had not been identified.
[src:infrastructure-drift/change-management-engineering] In the US, OSHA has regulations that govern how changes are to be made and documented.
[src:infrastructure-drift/change-management-engineering] The main requirement is that a thorough review of a proposed change be performed by a multi-disciplinary team to ensure that as many possible viewpoints are used to minimize the chances of missing a hazard.
[src:infrastructure-drift/change-management-engineering] In this context, change request management is known as Management of Change, or MOC.
[src:infrastructure-drift/change-management-engineering] It is just one of many components of Process Safety Management, section 1910.119(l).1.
[src:infrastructure-drift/configuration-management] CM applied over the lifecycle of a system provides visibility and control of its performance, functional, and physical attributes.
[src:infrastructure-drift/configuration-management] CM verifies that a system performs as intended, and is documented in sufficient detail to support its projected life cycle.
[src:infrastructure-drift/configuration-management] The CM process facilitates orderly management of system information and system changes for purposes such as to revise capability; improve performance, reliability, or maintainability; extend life; reduce costs; reduce risk and liability; or correct defects.
[src:infrastructure-drift/configuration-management] The relatively minimal cost of implementing CM is returned manyfold in cost avoidance.
[src:infrastructure-drift/configuration-management] The lack of CM (or its ineffectual implementation) can be very expensive and sometimes can have such catastrophic consequences such as failure of equipment or loss of life.
[src:infrastructure-drift/configuration-management] CM emphasizes the functional relation between parts, subsystems, and systems for effectively controlling system change.
[src:infrastructure-drift/configuration-management] It helps to verify that proposed changes are systematically considered to minimize adverse effects.
[src:infrastructure-drift/configuration-management] Changes to the system are proposed, evaluated, and implemented using a standardized, systematic approach that ensures consistency, and proposed changes are evaluated in terms of their anticipated impact on the entire system.
[src:infrastructure-drift/configuration-management] CM verifies that changes are carried out as specified and that documentation of items and systems reflects their true configuration.
[src:infrastructure-drift/configuration-management] A complete CM program includes provisions for the storing, tracking, and updating of all system information on a component, subsystem, and system basis.
[src:infrastructure-drift/configuration-management] A structured CM program ensures that documentation (e.g., requirements, design, test, and acceptance documentation) for items is accurate and consistent with the actual physical design of the item.
[src:infrastructure-drift/configuration-management] In many cases, without CM, the documentation exists but is not consistent with the item itself.
[src:infrastructure-drift/configuration-management] For this reason, engineers, contractors, and management are frequently forced to develop documentation reflecting the actual status of the item before they can proceed with a change.
[src:infrastructure-drift/configuration-management] This reverse engineering process is wasteful in terms of human and other resources and can be minimized or eliminated using CM.
[src:infrastructure-drift/configuration-management] Configuration management originated in the United States Department of Defense in the 1950s as a technical management discipline for hardware material items—and it is now a standard practice in virtually every industry.
[src:infrastructure-drift/configuration-management] The CM process became its own technical discipline in the late 1960s when the DoD developed a series of military standards called the "480 series" (i.e., MIL-STD-480, MIL-STD-481 and MIL-STD-483) that were subsequently issued in the 1970s.
[src:infrastructure-drift/configuration-management] This marked the beginning of what has now evolved into the most widely distributed and accepted standard on CM, ANSI–EIA–649–1998.
[src:infrastructure-drift/configuration-management] Many of these functions and models have redefined CM from its traditional holistic approach to technical management.
[src:infrastructure-drift/configuration-management] Some treat CM as being similar to a librarian activity and break out change control or change management as a separate or standalone discipline.
[src:infrastructure-drift/configuration-management] CM is the practice of handling changes systematically so that a system maintains its integrity over time.
[src:infrastructure-drift/configuration-management] CM implements the policies, procedures, techniques, and tools that manage, evaluate proposed changes, track change status, and maintain an inventory of system and support documents as the system changes.
[src:infrastructure-drift/configuration-management] CM programs and plans provide technical and administrative direction to the development and implementation of the procedures, functions, services, tools, processes, and resources required to successfully develop and support a complex system.
[src:infrastructure-drift/configuration-management] During system development, CM allows program management to track requirements throughout the life-cycle through acceptance and operations and maintenance.
[src:infrastructure-drift/configuration-management] As changes inevitably occur in the requirements and design, they must be approved and documented, creating an accurate record of the system status.
[src:infrastructure-drift/configuration-management] Ideally the CM process is applied throughout the system life cycle.
[src:infrastructure-drift/configuration-management] Many professionals mix up or get confused with Asset management (AM, see also ISO/IEC 19770), where it inventories the assets on hand.
[src:infrastructure-drift/configuration-management] The key difference between CM and AM is that the former does not manage the financial accounting aspect but the service that the system supports or in other words, that the latter (AM) is trying to realize value from an IT asset.
[src:infrastructure-drift/configuration-management] The CM process for both hardware and software configuration items comprises five distinct disciplines as established in the MIL–HDBK–61A and in ANSI/EIA-649.
[src:infrastructure-drift/configuration-management] Members of an organization interested in applying a standard change-management process will employ these disciplines as policies and procedures for establishing baselines, manage and control change, and monitor and assess the effectiveness and correctness of progress.
[src:infrastructure-drift/configuration-management] The IEEE 12207 process IEEE 12207.2 also has these activities and adds "Release management and delivery".
[src:infrastructure-drift/configuration-management] Configuration Identification (CI): consists of setting and maintaining baselines, which define the system or subsystem architecture, components, and any developments at any point in time.
[src:infrastructure-drift/configuration-management] It is the basis by which changes to any part of a system are identified, documented, and later tracked through design, development, testing, and final delivery.
[src:infrastructure-drift/configuration-management] CI incrementally establishes and maintains the definitive current basis for Configuration Status Accounting (CSA) of a system and its configuration items (CIs) throughout their life cycle (development, production, deployment, and operational support) until disposal.
[src:infrastructure-drift/configuration-management] Configuration Control: includes the evaluation of all change-requests and change-proposals, and their subsequent approval or disapproval.
[src:infrastructure-drift/configuration-management] It covers the process of controlling modifications to the system's design, hardware, firmware, software, and documentation.
[src:infrastructure-drift/configuration-management] Configuration Status Accounting: includes the process of recording and reporting configuration item descriptions (e.g., hardware, software, firmware, etc.) and all departures from the baseline during design and production.
[src:infrastructure-drift/configuration-management] In the event of suspected problems, operators can quickly verify baseline configuration and approved modifications.
[src:infrastructure-drift/configuration-management] Configuration Verification and Audit: an independent review of hardware and software for the purpose of assessing compliance with established performance requirements, commercial and appropriate military standards, and functional, allocated, and product baselines.
[src:infrastructure-drift/configuration-management] Configuration audits verify that the system and subsystem configuration documentation complies with the functional and physical performance characteristics before acceptance into an architectural baseline.
[src:infrastructure-drift/configuration-management] The software configuration management (SCM) process is looked upon by practitioners as the best solution to handling changes in software projects.
[src:infrastructure-drift/configuration-management] It identifies the functional and physical attributes of software at various points in time, and performs systematic control of changes to the identified attributes for the purpose of maintaining software integrity and traceability throughout the software development life cycle.
[src:infrastructure-drift/configuration-management] The SCM process further defines the need to trace changes, and the ability to verify that the final delivered software has all of the planned enhancements that are supposed to be included in the release.
[src:infrastructure-drift/configuration-management] It identifies four procedures that must be defined for each software project to ensure that a sound SCM process is implemented.
[src:infrastructure-drift/configuration-management] These terms and definitions can change somewhat from standard to standard.
[src:infrastructure-drift/configuration-management] ITIL specifies the use of a configuration management system (CMS) or configuration management database (CMDB) as a means of achieving industry best practices for Configuration Management.
[src:infrastructure-drift/configuration-management] CMS helps manage a federated collection of CMDBs.
[src:infrastructure-drift/configuration-management] The benefits of a CMS/CMDB includes being able to perform functions like root cause analysis, impact analysis, change management, and current state assessment for future state strategy development.
[src:infrastructure-drift/configuration-management] For information assurance, CM can be defined as the management of security features and assurances through control of changes made to hardware, software, firmware, documentation, test, test fixtures, and test documentation throughout the life cycle of an information system.
[src:infrastructure-drift/configuration-management] For example, configuration requirements may be different for a network firewall that functions as part of an organization's Internet boundary versus one that functions as an internal local network firewall.
[src:infrastructure-drift/configuration-management] Configuration management is used to maintain an understanding of the status of complex assets with a view to maintaining the highest level of serviceability for the lowest cost.
[src:infrastructure-drift/configuration-management] Specifically, it aims to ensure that operations are not disrupted due to the asset (or parts of the asset) overrunning limits of planned lifespan or below quality levels.
[src:infrastructure-drift/configuration-management] In the military, this type of activity is often classed as "mission readiness", and seeks to define which assets are available and for which type of mission; a classic example is whether aircraft on board an aircraft carrier are equipped with bombs for ground support or missiles for defense.
[src:infrastructure-drift/configuration-management] Configuration management can be used to maintain OS configuration files.
[src:infrastructure-drift/configuration-management] Many of these systems utilize Infrastructure as Code to define and maintain configuration.
[src:infrastructure-drift/configuration-management] The Promise theory of configuration maintenance was developed by Mark Burgess, with a practical implementation on present day computer systems in the software CFEngine able to perform real time repair as well as preventive maintenance.
[src:infrastructure-drift/configuration-management] Understanding the "as is" state of an asset and its major components is an essential element in preventive maintenance as used in maintenance, repair, and overhaul and enterprise asset management systems.
[src:infrastructure-drift/configuration-management] Complex assets such as aircraft, ships, industrial machinery etc. depend on many different components being serviceable.
[src:infrastructure-drift/configuration-management] This serviceability is often defined in terms of the amount of usage the component has had since it was new, since fitted, since repaired, the amount of use it has had over its life and several other limiting factors.
[src:infrastructure-drift/configuration-management] Understanding how near the end of their life each of these components is has been a major undertaking involving labor-intensive record keeping until recent developments in software.
[src:infrastructure-drift/configuration-management] Many types of component use electronic sensors to capture data which provides live condition monitoring.
[src:infrastructure-drift/configuration-management] This data is analyzed on board or at a remote location by computer to evaluate its current serviceability and increasingly its likely future state using algorithms which predict potential future failures based on previous examples of failure through field experience and modeling.
[src:infrastructure-drift/configuration-management] This is the basis for "predictive maintenance".
[src:infrastructure-drift/configuration-management] Availability of accurate and timely data is essential in order for CM to provide operational value and a lack of this can often be a limiting factor.
[src:infrastructure-drift/configuration-management] Capturing and disseminating the operating data to the various support organizations is becoming an industry in itself.
[src:infrastructure-drift/configuration-management] The consumers of this data have grown more numerous and complex with the growth of programs offered by original equipment manufacturers (OEMs).
[src:infrastructure-drift/configuration-management] These are designed to offer operators guaranteed availability and make the picture more complex with the operator managing the asset but the OEM taking on the liability to ensure its serviceability.
[src:infrastructure-drift/configuration-management] More recently configuration management has been applied to large construction projects which can often be very complex and have a huge number of details and changes that need to be documented.
[src:infrastructure-drift/configuration-management] Construction agencies such as the Federal Highway Administration have used configuration management for their infrastructure projects.
[src:infrastructure-drift/configuration-management] There are construction-based configuration management tools that aim to document change orders and RFIs in order to ensure a project stays on schedule and on budget.
[src:infrastructure-drift/configuration-management] These programs can also store information to aid in the maintenance and modification of the infrastructure when it is completed.
[src:infrastructure-drift/configuration-management] This study yielded results indicating a benefit to using configuration management on projects of this nature.
[src:infrastructure-drift/idempotence] The term was introduced by American mathematician Benjamin Peirce in 1870 in the context of elements of algebras that remain invariant when raised to a positive integer power, and literally means "(the quality of having) the same power", from *idem* + *potence* (same + power).
[src:infrastructure-drift/idempotence] If the set E has n elements, we can partition it into k chosen fixed points and $n-k$ non-fixed points under f , and then $k^{n-k}$ is the number of different idempotent functions.
[src:infrastructure-drift/idempotence] is the total number of possible idempotent functions on the set.
[src:infrastructure-drift/idempotence] Neither idempotence nor non-idempotence is preserved under function composition.
[src:infrastructure-drift/idempotence] As an example for the former, $f(x)=x$ mod 3 and $g(x)=\max(x,5)$ are both idempotent, but $f\circ g$ is not, although $g\circ f$ happens to be.
[src:infrastructure-drift/idempotence] As an example for the latter, the negation function $\neg$ on the Boolean domain is not idempotent, but $\neg \circ \neg$ is.
[src:infrastructure-drift/idempotence] Similarly, unary negation $-(\cdot )$ of real numbers is not idempotent, but $-(\cdot )\circ -(\cdot )$ is.
[src:infrastructure-drift/idempotence] In both cases, the composition is simply the identity function, which is idempotent.
[src:infrastructure-drift/idempotence] A morphism $f:x\to x$ in a category is called *idempotent* if $f\circ f=f$ .
[src:infrastructure-drift/idempotence] An idempotent is said to *split* if it can be written as $f=h\circ g$ for some $g:x\to y,\,h:y\to x$ with $g\circ h=\operatorname {id}$ .
[src:infrastructure-drift/idempotence] A category is said to be idempotent complete if every idempotent splits.
[src:infrastructure-drift/idempotence] For example, ${\mathsf {Set}}$ is idempotent complete.
[src:infrastructure-drift/idempotence] This is a very useful property in many situations, as it means that an operation can be repeated or retried as often as necessary without causing unintended effects.
[src:infrastructure-drift/idempotence] With non-idempotent operations, the algorithm may have to keep track of whether the operation was already performed or not.
[src:infrastructure-drift/idempotence] A function looking up a customer's name and address in a database is typically idempotent, since this will not cause the database to change.
[src:infrastructure-drift/idempotence] Similarly, a request for changing a customer's address to XYZ is typically idempotent, because the final address will be the same no matter how many times the request is submitted.
[src:infrastructure-drift/idempotence] However, a customer request for placing an order is typically not idempotent since multiple requests will lead to multiple orders being placed.
[src:infrastructure-drift/idempotence] A request for canceling a particular order is idempotent because no matter how many requests are made the order remains canceled.
[src:infrastructure-drift/idempotence] A sequence of idempotent subroutines where at least one subroutine is different from the others, however, is not necessarily idempotent if a later subroutine in the sequence changes a value that an earlier subroutine depends on—*idempotence is not closed under sequential composition*.
[src:infrastructure-drift/idempotence] For example, suppose the initial value of a variable is 3 and there is a subroutine sequence that reads the variable, then changes it to 5, and then reads it again.
[src:infrastructure-drift/idempotence] Each step in the sequence is idempotent: both steps reading the variable have no side effects and the step changing the variable to 5 will always have the same effect no matter how many times it is executed.
[src:infrastructure-drift/idempotence] Nonetheless, executing the entire sequence once produces the output (3, 5), but executing it a second time produces the output (5, 5), so the sequence is not idempotent.
[src:infrastructure-drift/idempotence] In the Hypertext Transfer Protocol (HTTP), idempotence and safety are the major attributes that separate HTTP methods.
[src:infrastructure-drift/idempotence] Of the major HTTP methods, GET, PUT, and DELETE should be implemented in an idempotent manner according to the standard, but POST doesn't need to be.
[src:infrastructure-drift/idempotence] GET retrieves the state of a resource; PUT updates the state of a resource; and DELETE deletes a resource.
[src:infrastructure-drift/idempotence] As in the example above, reading data usually has no side effects, so it is idempotent (in fact *nullipotent*).
[src:infrastructure-drift/idempotence] Updating and deleting a given data are each usually idempotent as long as the request uniquely identifies the resource and only that resource again in the future.
[src:infrastructure-drift/idempotence] PUT and DELETE with unique identifiers reduce to the simple case of assignment to a variable of either a value or the null-value, respectively, and are idempotent for the same reason; the end result is always the same as the result of the initial execution, even if the response differs.
[src:infrastructure-drift/idempotence] Violation of the unique identification requirement in storage or deletion typically causes violation of idempotence.
[src:infrastructure-drift/idempotence] Similarly, PUT and DELETE requests with nonspecific criteria may result in different outcomes depending on the state of the system – for example, a request to delete the most recent record.
[src:infrastructure-drift/idempotence] In each case, subsequent executions will further modify the state of the system, so they are not idempotent.
[src:infrastructure-drift/idempotence] In event stream processing, idempotence refers to the ability of a system to produce the same outcome, even if the same file, event or message is received more than once.
[src:infrastructure-drift/idempotence] In a load–store architecture, instructions that might possibly cause a page fault are idempotent.
[src:infrastructure-drift/idempotence] So if a page fault occurs, the operating system can load the page from disk and then simply re-execute the faulted instruction.
[src:infrastructure-drift/idempotence] In a processor where such instructions are not idempotent, dealing with page faults is much more complex.
[src:infrastructure-drift/idempotence] When reformatting output, pretty-printing is expected to be idempotent.
[src:infrastructure-drift/idempotence] In other words, if the output is already "pretty", there should be nothing to do for the pretty-printer.
[src:infrastructure-drift/idempotence] In service-oriented architecture (SOA), a multiple-step orchestration process composed entirely of idempotent steps can be replayed without side-effects if any part of that process fails.
[src:infrastructure-drift/idempotence] Many operations that are idempotent often have ways to "resume" a process if it is interrupted – ways that finish much faster than starting all over from the beginning.
[src:infrastructure-drift/idempotence] For example, resuming a file transfer, synchronizing files, creating a software build, installing an application and all of its dependencies with a package manager, etc.
[src:infrastructure-drift/idempotence] Applied examples that many people could encounter in their day-to-day lives include elevator call buttons and crosswalk buttons.
[src:infrastructure-drift/idempotence] The initial activation of the button moves the system into a requesting state, until the request is satisfied.
[src:infrastructure-drift/idempotence] Subsequent activations of the button between the initial activation and the request being satisfied have no effect, unless the system is designed to adjust the time for satisfying the request based on the number of activations.
[src:infrastructure-drift/idempotence] Similarly, the elevator "close" button may be pressed many times to the same effect as once, since the doors close on a fixed schedule – unless the "open" button is pressed.
[src:infrastructure-drift/idempotence] The "open" button is not idempotent, because each press adds further delay.
[src:infrastructure-drift/infrastructure-as-code] The concept of managing infrastructure through code emerged from early configuration management practices.
[src:infrastructure-drift/infrastructure-as-code] In the 1990s, tools such as CFEngine, created by Mark Burgess in 1993, introduced the idea of describing system configuration in a declarative language rather than executing manual commands, laying the intellectual groundwork for IaC.
[src:infrastructure-drift/infrastructure-as-code] IaC emerged as organizations began managing larger and more complex infrastructure, particularly with the growth of cloud computing and the need to provision resources consistently and at scale.
[src:infrastructure-drift/infrastructure-as-code] Treating infrastructure configuration like software - storing it in version control, reviewing it, and deploying it automatically allowed teams to reduce manual errors and reproduce environments reliably.
[src:infrastructure-drift/infrastructure-as-code] The ability to treat infrastructure as code and use the same tools as any other software project would allow developers to rapidly deploy applications.
[src:infrastructure-drift/infrastructure-as-code] The value of IaC can be broken down into three measurable categories: cost, speed, and risk.
[src:infrastructure-drift/infrastructure-as-code] Cost reduction aims at helping not only the enterprise financially, but also in terms of people and effort, meaning that by removing the manual component, organizations are able to refocus their efforts on other enterprise tasks.
[src:infrastructure-drift/infrastructure-as-code] Infrastructure automation enables speed through faster execution when configuring your infrastructure and provides visibility to help other teams across the enterprise work quickly and more efficiently.
[src:infrastructure-drift/infrastructure-as-code] Automation removes the risk associated with human error, like manual misconfiguration; removing this can decrease downtime and increase reliability.
[src:infrastructure-drift/infrastructure-as-code] These outcomes and attributes help the enterprise move toward implementing a culture of DevOps: the combined work of development and operations.
[src:infrastructure-drift/infrastructure-as-code] There are generally two approaches to IaC: declarative (functional) vs. imperative (procedural).
[src:infrastructure-drift/infrastructure-as-code] The difference between the declarative and the imperative approach is essentially *what* versus *how*.
[src:infrastructure-drift/infrastructure-as-code] The declarative approach focuses on what the eventual target configuration should be; the imperative focuses on how the infrastructure is to be changed to meet this.
[src:infrastructure-drift/infrastructure-as-code] The declarative approach defines the desired state and the system executes what needs to happen to achieve that desired state.
[src:infrastructure-drift/infrastructure-as-code] Imperative defines specific commands that need to be executed in the appropriate order to end with the desired conclusion.
[src:infrastructure-drift/infrastructure-as-code] Infrastructure as Code (IaC) allows organizations to manage servers and their configurations using code.
[src:infrastructure-drift/infrastructure-as-code] There are two ways to apply these configurations to servers: the 'push' and 'pull' methods.
[src:infrastructure-drift/infrastructure-as-code] In the 'push' method, the system controlling the configuration directly sends instructions to the server.
[src:infrastructure-drift/infrastructure-as-code] In the 'pull' method, the server retrieves its own instructions from the controlling system.
[src:infrastructure-drift/infrastructure-as-code] There are many tools that fulfill infrastructure automation capabilities and use IaC.
[src:infrastructure-drift/infrastructure-as-code] Broadly speaking, any framework or tool that performs changes or configures infrastructure declaratively or imperatively based on a programmatic approach can be considered IaC.
[src:infrastructure-drift/infrastructure-as-code] Traditionally, server (lifecycle) automation and configuration management tools were used to accomplish IaC.
[src:infrastructure-drift/infrastructure-as-code] Now enterprises are also using continuous configuration automation tools or stand-alone IaC frameworks, such as Microsoft’s PowerShell DSC or AWS CloudFormation.
[src:infrastructure-drift/infrastructure-as-code] All continuous configuration automation (CCA) tools can be thought of as extensions of traditional IaC frameworks.
[src:infrastructure-drift/infrastructure-as-code] They leverage IaC to change, configure, and automate infrastructure, and they also provide visibility, efficiency, and flexibility in how infrastructure is managed.
[src:infrastructure-drift/infrastructure-as-code] These additional attributes provide enterprise-level security and compliance.
[src:infrastructure-drift/infrastructure-as-code] Community content is a key determinant of an open-source CCA tool's quality.
[src:infrastructure-drift/infrastructure-as-code] According to Gartner, the value of CCA tools is "as dependent on user-community-contributed content and support as it is on the commercial maturity and performance of the automation tooling".
[src:infrastructure-drift/infrastructure-as-code] Established vendors such as Puppet and Chef have created their own communities.
[src:infrastructure-drift/infrastructure-as-code] Chef has Chef Community Repository and Puppet has PuppetForge.
[src:infrastructure-drift/infrastructure-as-code] Other vendors rely on adjacent communities and leverage other IaC frameworks such as PowerShell DSC.
[src:infrastructure-drift/infrastructure-as-code] New vendors are emerging that are not content-driven, but model-driven with the intelligence in the product to deliver content.
[src:infrastructure-drift/infrastructure-as-code] These visual, object-oriented systems work well for developers, but they are especially useful to production-oriented DevOps and operations constituents that value models versus scripting for content.
[src:infrastructure-drift/infrastructure-as-code] As the field continues to develop and change, the community-based content will become ever more important to how IaC tools are used, unless they are model-driven and object-oriented.
[src:infrastructure-drift/infrastructure-as-code] Other tools include AWS CloudFormation, cdist, StackStorm, Juju, and Step CI.
[src:infrastructure-drift/infrastructure-as-code] IaC can be a key attribute of enabling best practices in DevOps.
[src:infrastructure-drift/infrastructure-as-code] Developers become more involved in defining configuration and Ops teams get involved earlier in the development process.
[src:infrastructure-drift/infrastructure-as-code] Tools that utilize IaC bring visibility to the state and configuration of servers and ultimately provide the visibility to users within the enterprise, which brings teams together to maximize their efforts.
[src:infrastructure-drift/infrastructure-as-code] Automation in general aims to take the confusion and error-prone aspect of manual processes and make it more efficient, and productive.
[src:infrastructure-drift/infrastructure-as-code] Allowing for better software and applications to be created with flexibility, less downtime, and an overall cost-effective way for the company.
[src:infrastructure-drift/infrastructure-as-code] IaC is intended to reduce the complexity that kills efficiency out of manual configuration.
[src:infrastructure-drift/infrastructure-as-code] Automation and collaboration are considered central points in DevOps; infrastructure automation tools are often included as components of a DevOps toolchain.
[src:infrastructure-drift/infrastructure-as-code] The 2020 Cloud Threat Report released by Unit 42 (the threat intelligence unit of cybersecurity provider Palo Alto Networks) identified around 200,000 potential vulnerabilities in infrastructure-as-code templates.
[src:infrastructure-drift/resource-drift] The Terraform state file is a record of all resources Terraform manages.
[src:infrastructure-drift/resource-drift] You should not make manual changes to resources controlled by Terraform, because the state file will be out of sync, or "drift," from the real infrastructure.
[src:infrastructure-drift/resource-drift] If your state and configuration do not match your infrastructure, Terraform will attempt to reconcile your infrastructure, which may unintentionally destroy or recreate resources.
[src:infrastructure-drift/resource-drift] In this tutorial, you will detect and fix differences between your state file and real infrastructure.
[src:infrastructure-drift/resource-drift] First, you will create an EC2 instance and security group with Terraform.
[src:infrastructure-drift/resource-drift] Then, you will manually edit them via the AWS CLI.
[src:infrastructure-drift/resource-drift] Next, you will identify and resolve the discrepancies between Terraform state and your infrastructure.
[src:infrastructure-drift/resource-drift] Drift detection is available in HCP Terraform **Standard** Edition.
[src:infrastructure-drift/resource-drift] Refer to HCP Terraform pricing for details.
[src:infrastructure-drift/resource-drift] This tutorial assumes you are familiar with the standard Terraform workflow.
[src:infrastructure-drift/resource-drift] If you are unfamiliar with Terraform, complete the Get Started tutorials first.
[src:infrastructure-drift/resource-drift] Start by cloning the example repository.
[src:infrastructure-drift/resource-drift] This configuration builds an EC2 instance, an SSH key pair, and a security group rule to allow SSH access to the instance.
[src:infrastructure-drift/resource-drift] Create an SSH key pair in your current directory, replacing `your_email@example.com` with your email address.
[src:infrastructure-drift/resource-drift] Open the `terraform.tfvars` file and edit the region to match your AWS CLI configuration.
[src:infrastructure-drift/resource-drift] Open the `main.tf` file and review your configuration.
[src:infrastructure-drift/resource-drift] The main resources are your EC2 instance, your key pair, and the SSH security group.
[src:infrastructure-drift/resource-drift] Enter `yes` when prompted to accept your changes.
[src:infrastructure-drift/resource-drift] When your apply operation completes, run `terraform state list` to review the resources managed by Terraform in your state file.
[src:infrastructure-drift/resource-drift] To introduce a change to your configuration outside the Terraform workflow, create a new security group with the AWS CLI and export that value as an environment variable.
[src:infrastructure-drift/resource-drift] Confirm you created the environment variable.
[src:infrastructure-drift/resource-drift] This will return the security group you just created.
[src:infrastructure-drift/resource-drift] Next, create a new rule for your group to provide TCP access to the instance on port 8080.
[src:infrastructure-drift/resource-drift] Associate the security group you created manually with the EC2 instance provisioned by Terraform.
[src:infrastructure-drift/resource-drift] Now, you have replaced your instance's SSH security group with a new security group that is not tracked in the Terraform state file.
[src:infrastructure-drift/resource-drift] By default, Terraform compares your state file to real infrastructure whenever you invoke `terraform plan` or `terraform apply`.
[src:infrastructure-drift/resource-drift] The refresh updates your state file in-memory to reflect the actual configuration of your infrastructure.
[src:infrastructure-drift/resource-drift] This ensures that Terraform determines the correct changes to make to your resources.
[src:infrastructure-drift/resource-drift] If you suspect that your infrastructure configuration changed outside of the Terraform workflow, you can use a `-refresh-only` flag to inspect what the changes to your state file would be.
[src:infrastructure-drift/resource-drift] This is safer than the `refresh` subcommand, which automatically overwrites your state file without displaying the updates.
[src:infrastructure-drift/resource-drift] The `-refresh-only` flag was introduced in Terraform 0.15.4, and is preferred over the `terraform refresh` subcommand.
[src:infrastructure-drift/resource-drift] Run `terraform plan -refresh-only` to determine the drift between your current state file and actual configuration.
[src:infrastructure-drift/resource-drift] As shown in the output, Terraform has detected differences between the infrastructure and the current state, and sees that your original security group allowing access on port 22 is no longer attached to your EC2 instance.
[src:infrastructure-drift/resource-drift] The refresh-only plan output indicates that Terraform will update your state file to modify the configuration of your EC2 instance to reflect the new security group with access on port 8080.
[src:infrastructure-drift/resource-drift] Apply these changes to make your state file match your real infrastructure, but not your Terraform configuration.
[src:infrastructure-drift/resource-drift] A refresh-only operation does not attempt to modify your infrastructure to match your Terraform configuration -- it only gives you the option to review and track the drift in your state file.
[src:infrastructure-drift/resource-drift] If you ran `terraform plan` or `terraform apply` without the `-refresh-only` flag now, Terraform would attempt to revert your manual changes.
[src:infrastructure-drift/resource-drift] Instead, you will update your configuration to associate your EC2 instance with both security groups.
[src:infrastructure-drift/resource-drift] Import the `sg_web` security group resource to your state file to bring it under Terraform management.
[src:infrastructure-drift/resource-drift] First, add the resource definition to your configuration by adding a new security group resource and rule resource to your `main.tf` file.
[src:infrastructure-drift/resource-drift] Add the security group ID to your instance resource.
[src:infrastructure-drift/resource-drift] This tutorial uses `terraform import` to bring infrastructure under Terraform management.
[src:infrastructure-drift/resource-drift] Terraform 1.5+ supports configuration-driven import, which lets you import multiple resources at once, review the import in your plan-and-apply workflow, and generate configuration for imported resources.
[src:infrastructure-drift/resource-drift] Review the import tutorial to learn more.
[src:infrastructure-drift/resource-drift] Run `terraform import` to associate your resource definition with the security group created in the AWS CLI.
[src:infrastructure-drift/resource-drift] Run `terraform state list` to return the list of resources Terraform is managing, which now includes the imported resources.
[src:infrastructure-drift/resource-drift] Terraform successfully associated both security groups with the instance in state.
[src:infrastructure-drift/resource-drift] However, your instance still only allows port 8080 access because the `modify-instance-attribute` AWS CLI command detached the SSH security group.
[src:infrastructure-drift/resource-drift] Now that the `sg_web` security group is represented in state, re-run `terraform apply` to associate the SSH security group with your EC2 instance.
[src:infrastructure-drift/resource-drift] Notice how this updates your EC2 instance's security group to include *both* the security groups allowing SSH and `8080`.
[src:infrastructure-drift/resource-drift] Enter `yes` when prompted to confirm your changes.
[src:infrastructure-drift/resource-drift] Enter `yes` when prompted to connect to the instance.
[src:infrastructure-drift/resource-drift] Exit the SSH connection by typing `exit` in the SSH prompt.
[src:infrastructure-drift/resource-drift] Confirm your instance allows port 8080 access.
[src:infrastructure-drift/resource-drift] When you are finished with this tutorial, destroy the resources you created.
[src:infrastructure-drift/resource-drift] In this tutorial, you created an EC2 instance and security group deployment with Terraform.
[src:infrastructure-drift/resource-drift] Then, you introduced drift by editing your security groups outside the Terraform workflow.
[src:infrastructure-drift/resource-drift] Finally, you learned how to detect your drifted configuration with `-refresh-only` operations and how to reconcile your state file and configuration with the Terraform CLI refresh and import commands.
[src:infrastructure-drift/software-configuration-management] With the introduction of cloud computing and DevOps the purposes of SCM tools have become merged in some cases.
[src:infrastructure-drift/software-configuration-management] The SCM tools themselves have become virtual appliances that can be instantiated as virtual machines and saved with state and version.
[src:infrastructure-drift/software-configuration-management] The tools can model and manage cloud-based virtual resources, including virtual appliances, storage units, and software bundles.
[src:infrastructure-drift/software-configuration-management] The roles and responsibilities of the actors have become merged as well with developers now being able to dynamically instantiate virtual servers and related resources.
[src:infrastructure-drift/software-configuration-management] The history of software configuration management (SCM) can be traced back as early as the 1950s, when CM (configuration management), originally for hardware development and production control, was being applied to software development.
[src:infrastructure-drift/software-configuration-management] Early software had a physical footprint, such as cards, tapes, and other media.
[src:infrastructure-drift/software-configuration-management] The first software configuration management was a manual operation.
[src:infrastructure-drift/software-configuration-management] With the advances in language and complexity, software engineering, involving configuration management and other methods, became a major concern due to issues like schedule, budget, and quality.
[src:infrastructure-drift/software-configuration-management] Practical lessons, over the years, had led to the definition, and establishment, of procedures and tools.
[src:infrastructure-drift/software-configuration-management] Eventually, the tools became systems to manage software changes.
[src:infrastructure-drift/software-configuration-management] Industry-wide practices were offered as solutions, either in an open or proprietary manner (such as Revision Control System).
[src:infrastructure-drift/software-configuration-management] With the growing use of computers, systems emerged that handled a broader scope, including requirements management, design alternatives, quality control, and more; later tools followed the guidelines of organizations, such as the Capability Maturity Model of the Software Engineering Institute.
[src:infrastructure-drift/system-administration] An **IT administrator**, **system administrator**, **sysadmin**, or **admin** is a person who is responsible for the upkeep, configuration, and reliable operation of computer systems, especially multi-user computers, such as servers.
[src:infrastructure-drift/system-administration] The system administrator seeks to ensure that the uptime, performance, resources, and security of the computers they manage meet the needs of the users, without exceeding a set budget when doing so.
[src:infrastructure-drift/system-administration] To meet these needs, a system administrator may acquire, install, or upgrade computer components and software; provide routine automation; maintain security policies; troubleshoot; train or supervise staff; or offer technical support for projects.
[src:infrastructure-drift/system-administration] Many organizations offer jobs related to system administration.
[src:infrastructure-drift/system-administration] In a larger company, these may all be separate positions within a computer support or Information Services (IS) department.
[src:infrastructure-drift/system-administration] In a smaller group, they may be shared by a few sysadmins, or even a single person.
[src:infrastructure-drift/system-administration] Most employers require a bachelor's degree in a related field, such as computer science, information technology, electronics engineering, or computer engineering.
[src:infrastructure-drift/system-administration] Some schools also offer undergraduate degrees and graduate programs in system administration.
[src:infrastructure-drift/system-administration] In addition, because of the practical nature of system administration and the easy availability of open-source server software, many system administrators enter the field self-taught.
[src:infrastructure-drift/system-administration] Generally, a prospective employee will be required to have experience with the computer systems they are expected to manage.
[src:infrastructure-drift/system-administration] Sometimes, almost exclusively in smaller sites, the role of system administrator may be given to a skilled user in addition to or in replacement of their duties.
[src:infrastructure-drift/system-administration] The *subject matter* of system administration includes computer systems and the ways people use them in an organization.
[src:infrastructure-drift/system-administration] This entails a knowledge of operating systems and applications, as well as hardware and software troubleshooting, but also knowledge of the purposes for which people in the organization use the computers.
[src:infrastructure-drift/system-administration] Perhaps the most important skill for a system administrator is problem solving—frequently under various sorts of constraints and stress.
[src:infrastructure-drift/system-administration] The sysadmin is on call when a computer system goes down or malfunctions, and must be able to quickly and correctly diagnose what is wrong and how best to fix it.
[src:infrastructure-drift/system-administration] They may also need to have teamwork and communication skills, as well as being able to install and configure hardware and software.
[src:infrastructure-drift/system-administration] Sysadmins must understand the behavior of software in order to deploy it and to troubleshoot problems, and generally know several programming languages used for scripting or automation of routine tasks.
[src:infrastructure-drift/system-administration] A typical sysadmin's role is not to design or write new application software but when they are responsible for automating system or application configuration with various configuration management tools, the lines somewhat blur.
[src:infrastructure-drift/system-administration] Depending on the sysadmin's role and skillset, they may be expected to understand equivalent key/core concepts a software engineer understands.
[src:infrastructure-drift/system-administration] That said, system administrators are not software engineers or developers, in the job title sense.
[src:infrastructure-drift/system-administration] Particularly when dealing with Internet-facing or business-critical systems, a sysadmin must have a strong grasp of computer security.
[src:infrastructure-drift/system-administration] This includes not merely deploying software patches, but also preventing break-ins and other security problems with preventive measures.
[src:infrastructure-drift/system-administration] In some organizations, computer security administration is a separate role responsible for overall security and the upkeep of firewalls and intrusion detection systems, but all sysadmins are generally responsible for the security of computer systems.
[src:infrastructure-drift/system-administration] In larger organizations, some of the tasks above may be divided among different system administrators or members of different organizational groups.
[src:infrastructure-drift/system-administration] For example, a dedicated individual(s) may apply all system upgrades, a Quality Assurance (QA) team may perform testing and validation, and one or more technical writers may be responsible for all technical documentation written for a company.
[src:infrastructure-drift/system-administration] System administrators, in larger organizations, tend not to be systems architects, systems engineers, or systems designers.
[src:infrastructure-drift/system-administration] In smaller organizations, the system administrator might also act as technical support, database administrator, network administrator, storage (SAN) administrator or application analyst.
[src:infrastructure-drift/system-administration] Bureau of Labor Statistics (BLS) Occupational Outlook predicts a decline for System Administrators of -4 percent from 2024 to 2034.
